b'The lyrics criticize all this fake New age- instagram- hippie era we are living, where people are pretending to be someone in social media to be liked or love but they are different in real life. #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'Bestiario is track #10 and the last song of this album. It\xe2\x80\x99s kind of a tribute to Portishead and other UK bands but at the same time sounds like our old selves! #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/GXgTemz7H2'
b'@karen_mullen_m no importa, despues ponemos el link para que le des replay'
b'RT @EDouglasWW: @zoetheband This song could have easily  been on Disintegration but I like the mood amidst all the poppier songs.'
b'#TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/TwEi6YNawX'
b'RT @centralzoebr: Fiebre as well as the next two are different from the previous ones, loaded with a harsher criticism and a greater force\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'Rodrigo (drums) had watched a The Cure documentary where they talk about the big and monolithic drums on their songs, that rhythmically support or carry all the song. It\xe2\x80\x99s becomes repetitive and instrospective , so you start to lose yourself in the song #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/yMGVV1ngxL'
b'Ese cuadro no me pinta, track #9: This is the longest and \xe2\x80\x9cweirdest\xe2\x80\x9d song of the record, it has a repetitive drum pattern. #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
b'Watch Fiebre\xe2\x80\x99s video here https://t.co/lGpmhZINgP #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'It\xe2\x80\x99s about this hyperconnectivity and consumerism we are living in, we are missing things in real life because we spend most of our time watching a screen, the chorus says: you are no going to silence me, you will not turn me into a robot  #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
b'FIEBRE, track #8:  The intro reminds us of Tubular Bells by Mike Oldfield, then it evolves and becomes an energetic song #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'The lyrics are about a boy asking his father some questions about life, it\xe2\x80\x99s a song where we could explore and build a musical landscape #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/wraN5sl3cY'

b'TEPOZTL\xc3\x81N, track #7. Sergio had this idea for a song at the end of 2019, he made it with acoustic guitar while he was at Tepoztl\xc3\xa1n (a place in M\xc3\xa9xico). #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'It is a tribute to Phil Collins , Elton John or Rod Stewart, even maybe like a Beck ballad but with 70s rock inspired drums. The lyrics are inspired in the Nostradamus writings. #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'Canci\xc3\xb3n de Cuna para Marte, track #6, is a darker ballad that started with a composition by Angel (bass player) and then each one of us gave other ideas to build the song, the result was a calm and introspective song #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/8lEE7vPp2w'
b'...""we noticed everything had a characteristic sound and we had similar ideas, so we are connected and have this "karmic" sonic identity  #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/HqbNg7akiU'
b'The title has to do with the way we are synchronized as a band: even though we were away from each other when we started preparing the demos for this album... #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
b'SKR is the abbreviation of "Sonidos de Karm\xc3\xa1tica Resonancia" (the title of the album) or in English: Sounds of Karmic Resonance #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/g3h1qhtj13'

b'SKR, track #5, was the first single of this album. It has an electronic part but the chorus has guitars and a classic rock sound. It talks about love and the video reminds us of the Walt Disney 1940 animated film \xe2\x80\x9cFantasia\xe2\x80\x9d  https://t.co/efXdTJHYvg #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
b"Watch El Duelo's video here \xe2\x9a\x94\xef\xb8\x8f\xf0\x9f\x90\x89 https://t.co/HNg652xDzy #TimsTwitterListeningParty"

b'EL DUELO, track #4, was written by @Sergiorussek our guitar player (lyrics and music) and it\xe2\x80\x99s a song that talks about leaving someone in order to find and love yourself, #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b"RT @monophonicgirl: #TimsTwitterListeningParty \xf0\x9f\x87\xb2\xf0\x9f\x87\xbd The bass in \xe2\x80\x9cVelur\xe2\x80\x9d sounds so much like The Cure. There's no denying their influences  @L\xe2\x80\xa6"
b'This album is a tribute to all the things that have inspired us and have made us the band we are right now!  Watch the video here: https://t.co/DgO4Xc4zQk #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'VELUR is inspired in Soda Stereo and The Cure and at the same time it is like a modern version of one of our own songs: \xe2\x80\x9cNo me destruyas\xe2\x80\x9d (part of the record we listened last time with you: Memo Rex and El Coraz\xc3\xb3n At\xc3\xb3mico de la V\xc3\xada L\xc3\xa1ctea ) #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
b"RT @EDouglasWW: I'm sure part of what I love about @zoetheband is their heavy use of synthesizers and keyboards... #TimsTwitterListeningPar\xe2\x80\xa6"
b"RT @monophonicgirl: #TimsTwitterListeningParty \xf0\x9f\x87\xb2\xf0\x9f\x87\xbd Karmadame's video has a special mystique. At times it reminds me of the films of Alejandr\xe2\x80\xa6"

b'The cover art of the album is the work of the great artist and designer Pedro Friedeberg. He is known for his surreal art and the use of lines, patterns, colors and symbols. You can learn more about his work here: https://t.co/HgvYhbwQsf #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/uEFxFPnZVs'

b'In this song and in SKR (song #5) you can see the influence of what @LeonBenLarregui was studying at that time: gnosticism and the Dead Sea Scrolls. Gnostics talk about Sophia, a feminine figure of primordial energy and wisdom portrayed in both songs #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'KARMADAME
The lyrics of this song are very positive and may resonate with other people. It\xe2\x80\x99s a very spiritual song about Karma and Dharma, it has a funky- bossa nova sound with lots of synths and keyboards. watch the video here:
https://t.co/E22q1Z2FcO
#TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'We made this album in a raw and organic way, playing and recording together. With the lockdown we had limited time ,but that made us focus and somehow it was helpful for the creative process. #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
b'@soozworld @listening_party @Tim_Burgess thanks!!'

b'Eduardo de la Paz was the recording engineer, assisted by Juan Sebasti\xc3\xa1n Rodr\xc3\xadguez and Mario Fr\xc3\xadas, and of course, all the @panoramstudios team was essential to the creation of this record!  #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cPopular\xe2\x80\x9d the song you are listening right now, is an upbeat opening song that talks about a highschool boy that can\xe2\x80\x99t be with a girl because he is not popular enough. This is the video: https://t.co/XRh4ScWxz3 #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
b'The other 6 songs were recorded in november ,after lots of things had changed in the world (because of the Covid lockdown). It was produced by Craig Silvey and us. #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'"Sonidos de Karm\xc3\xa1tica Resonancia" is our 7th studio album, it came out in april of this year. The first 4 songs of this album were recorded in @PanoramStudios in January 2020 #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b"Those were all the songs, we hope you liked Memo Rex Commander y el Coraz\xc3\xb3n At\xc3\xb3mico de la V\xc3\xada L\xc3\xa1ctea  and we just released our new album a couple of days ago! it's called Sonidos de Karm\xc3\xa1tica Resonancia, you can find it here. https://t.co/KNJmq3vsCd #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/7q6glScUOv"
b'Paz is a very experimental yet easy to listen to and dance all the way through the end.   Great ending chapter for the album.(@R_guardiola) #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'13- Paz\nwhat a fun track. No clue on where the structure is going which is something I usually love in songs: To feel lost inside their structures. It is just a crazy long build-up towards the upbeat part. (@R_guardiola) #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
b'Love this track. Love the sound and the emotions in it.  Very powerful. \nI was blown away by the mix. One of the best sounding tracks from the album. (@R_guardiola) #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'12. Side Effects: another one with lyrics in English and ultra slow one. We really went for the slow ones in this album!!! \nAWESOME track. I really wish we would have done a spanish version for this song!!!!! it could be a classic. (@R_guardiola) #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'"Triste Sister" is also one of my favorite tracks while we toured this album.\nI really enjoyed playing this song live. Good memories. \nit was not very popular though hahaha.  It\xe2\x80\x99s a great B-side and a memorable track from this album. (@R_guardiola) #TimsTwitterListeningParty https://t.co/WWl7qbfMC5'

b"11- Triste Sister\na true gem, I (@yoAngelMosqueda) don't remember very well how we made this song but it's part of our musical evolution. There are hints of psychedelia and it is a more sofisticated song #TimsTwitterListeningParty"

b'9- Paula\nwe couldn\xe2\x80\x99t find a proper drum pattern simple enough for the verses to shine, so I was in our rehearsal room in Coyoac\xc3\xa1n. I grabbed a shaker with my right hand and just played bass and snare while doing it, it finally took off! (@R_guardiola) #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'8. The Room: what a crazy song \xf0\x9f\x98\x84. I love how this album really explored with this ultra slow songs. It gave it a lot of it\xe2\x80\x99s character. It was all about the contrast between the pop up beat songs and this dark ultra slow tracks. (@R_guardiola) #TimsTwitterListeningParty'

b'6- Mrs Nitro: it shows without a doubt our darkest or "goth" side, great instrument arrangements. Phil\'s hand can be noticed on the instrumentation and the way the song is structured. Great work from Phil  (@yoAngelMosqueda) #TimsTwitterListeningParty'
